{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/pancreatitis-acute/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"d870d218-25f0-5c41-905f-a5aa76957a7a","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 1aadcc4e-b6bd-4780-a095-cecf9bf76bd9 --><h1>Pancreatitis - acute: Summary</h1><!-- end field 1aadcc4e-b6bd-4780-a095-cecf9bf76bd9 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item d19135e7-5744-469d-9af5-2fd313376837 --><!-- begin field 58a423e3-347e-4943-87ef-19fe11c5d494 --><ul><li>Acute pancreatitis is an acute inflammatory process of the pancreas with varying involvement of local tissues or more remote organ systems.<ul><li>Mild acute pancreatitis is characterized by the absence of complications (local or systemic) or organ dysfunction. It usually has an uneventful recovery.</li><li>Moderately severe acute pancreatitis is characterized by local complications and/or transient organ dysfunction which resolves within 48 hours. </li><li>Severe acute pancreatitis is characterized by persistent organ dysfunction (failure to resolve in 48 hours) and often leads to local complications such as pancreatic necrosis, abscess, and pseudocyst formation.</li><li>Recurrent acute pancreatitis is characterized by distinct episodes of acute pancreatitis with full recovery between episodes.</li></ul></li><li>Acute pancreatitis is most commonly caused by gallstones or alcohol misuse. Other causes include endoscopic procedures, trauma, surgery, metabolic conditions (such as hypertriglyceridaemia and hypercalcaemia), infections (such as mumps, coxsackie B4 virus, and <em>Mycoplasma pneumonia</em>), and drugs (such as thiazide diuretics, azathioprine, tetracyclines, and oestrogens).</li><li>The mortality rate for acute pancreatitis ranges from 1% in mild acute pancreatitis to 10–25% in severe acute pancreatitis.</li><li>Acute pancreatitis should be suspected in any person with acute upper or generalized abdominal pain, particularly if they have a history or clinical features of gallstones or alcohol misuse.<br></li><li>A person with suspected acute pancreatitis should be admitted urgently to hospital.</li><ul><li>Admission should not be delayed by taking blood samples or ordering imaging in primary care.<br></li></ul></ul><!-- end field 58a423e3-347e-4943-87ef-19fe11c5d494 --><!-- end item d19135e7-5744-469d-9af5-2fd313376837 -->","topic":{"id":"a1189e29-6f67-5025-b150-794cebf1fefb","topicId":"dd099a94-8039-4337-a80f-f1f38b3dd527","topicName":"Pancreatitis - acute","slug":"pancreatitis-acute","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"d870d218-25f0-5c41-905f-a5aa76957a7a","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"43d71289-ccc5-5801-a291-bc4293cb7be7","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5b86d125-7a89-5ed9-8e1e-9cfb327fb730","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"8e52c919-a50f-5e5d-adaf-b38509b533a7","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"0668e858-fffc-5cc8-8db1-671c009ce053","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"4a20c5c0-04c7-5fdb-a3e6-1679b32664de","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"e9997699-b9ad-55c1-8ddd-b66e79424b2f","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"95bb5a93-987a-5aed-ae96-377205c8189e","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"522c0d3c-6ce2-5a08-b5b5-77786aa3be6c","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"6c908222-123d-5e26-9c6b-acb3fa8474cd","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"d166f794-86aa-5999-8353-fa36f0b7e12e","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"baafb08d-907d-583d-a10d-43f0b29071b0","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality Standards"}]},{"id":"a592f6a4-e0